'''<U+00C1>ngel Daniel Vassallo Col<U+00F3>n''' (born April 21, 1986) is a [[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]] professional [[basketball]] player who plays [[small forward]] for the [[Ligue Nationale de Basketball]]'s (LNB) [[ASVEL Lyon-Villeurbanne]]. After completing his high school education, he played for the Tigers of Hargrave Military Academy, reaching the preparatory national finals. Vassallo joined the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] playing for [[Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University|Virginia Tech]]. Throughout his college career,  Vassallo received several recognitions, including two All-ACC second team inclusions. He finished fifth in the campus' all-time scoring list. In his first [[Baloncesto Superior Nacional]] season,  Vassallo averaged 25.6 points, 6.7 rebounds, and 4.3 assists per game for the [[Criollos de Caguas (basketball)|Criollos de Caguas]]. He made his LNB debut for [[Paris-Levallois Basket]], leading the team to the playoffs. Vassallo has been an All-Star player in both the BSN and LNB.

He has been a member of the [[Puerto Rico national basketball team]] since his teenage years, representing [[Puerto Rico]] in the 2003 FIBA World Championship for Junior Men and the 2005 FIBA U-21 World Championship. In 2008, Vassallo joined the senior team, playing at the [[2008 Centrobasket]], [[FIBA Americas Championship 2009]] and [[2010 FIBA World Championship]].

==Early life==
Vassallo was born on April 21, 1986, in the municipality of [[Toa Baja, Puerto Rico|Toa Baja]], located in the northern coast of Puerto Rico's main island. He was the younger of two siblings born to <U+00C1>ngel Vassallo and Maria Col<U+00F3>n, along his brother, Alexis Vassallo.<ref name="NCAA"/> His father was a former professional player in the Baloncesto Superior Nacional, playing 17 seasons and becoming one of the league<U+2019>s all-time leading scorers.<ref name="NCAA"/>

In 2001, Vassallo moved to Virginia, where he continued his secondary education. He then enrolled in Faith Christian Academy, where he finished his high school education, being lettered in basketball and baseball.<ref name="NCAA"/> Vassallo played for the team three years, leading it in scoring in all of them. Subsequently, he continued preparatory education and played for the Tigers of [[Hargrave Military Academy]].<ref name="NCAA"/> The team finished the season with a record of 28-1, advancing to the preparatory national championship game, losing to Laurinburg. In this game, Vassallo scored 19 points and recovered 14 rebounds.<ref name="NCAA"/>

==National Collegiate Athletic Association==
Vassallo signed with [[University of Richmond]] twice, being denied admission both times despite meeting the requirements.<ref name="TechHoops">{{cite web| url=http://techhoops.com/hokie-career-recordsleaders/former-players/40-ad-vassallo/| title=40 A.D. Vassallo| publisher=TechHoops.com| accessdate=2010-07-17}}</ref> Richmond eventually traded his rights to [[Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University|Virginia Tech]] as collateral in a previous trade for Tony Dobbins. Vassallo debuted for the Hokies in the 2005-06 season, playing in all of the team's games. Despite mostly serving as a bench player, he played at least 20 minutes in games against [[Mount St. Mary's University|Mount St. Mary's]] and [[Marshall University|Marshall]], scoring 18 collective points, 5 rebounds, 2 assists and one blocked shot.<ref name="NCAA">{{cite web| url=http://www.hokiesports.com/mbasketball/players/2008/vassallo.html| title=40 - A.D. Vassallo (2008)| publisher=[[Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University]]| accessdate=2010-07-18}}</ref> His first NCAA start was against [[Radford University|Radford]], recording 7 points, 3 rebounds and 3 assists. In a game against [[Western Carolina University|Western Carolina]], Vassallo scored his first 3-point field goal.<ref name="NCAA"/> Vassallo scored season best in three-point baskets and rebounds against [[Morgan State University|Morgan State]]. He started in a game at Bowling Green, but played less that ten minutes. Vassallo recorded his first double-double against [[Wake Forest University|Wake Forest]], scoring 29 points and recovering 10 rebounds.<ref name="NCAA"/> He set season bests in six categories, shooting 11 out of 19 2-point field goals, 4-of-5 3-point field goals, 3of-3 free throws and earning four steals. The 29 points were the highest amount scored by a Virginia Tech freshman in 27 years. Vassallo set a season-high 7 assists against [[University of Virginia|Virginia]].<ref name="NCAA"/> He was included in the starting lineup in 8 out of the last 11 season games. At the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] (ACC) [[ACC Men's Basketball Tournament|Tournament]] he scored 6 points and recovered 3 rebounds against Virginia.<ref name="NCAA"/> In his first season, Vassallo led the Hokies in free throw percentage, he was also an Honorable Mention ACC All-Freshman and two-time ACC Rookie of the Week. He continued serving as the Hokies backup small forward in the 2006-07 season.  Vassallo scored 15 points in Virginia Tech's first home game. In 22 minutes against [[University of West Florida|West Florida]] he scored 26 points, recovered 6 rebounds and recorded a block.<ref name="NCAA"/> He set a career-high in free throws against [[Southern Illinois University|Southern Illinois]]. Serving as a starter against [[University of Richmond|Richmond]], Vassallo recorded 11 points and 6 rebounds. While serving as a backup he scored in double digits against [[University of North Carolina at Greensboro|UNC Greensboro]], [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|North Carolina]] and [[University of Miami|Miami]].<ref name="NCAA"/> He recorded a double-double in his next start with 19 points and 10 rebounds. Serving as starter against Virginia, Vassallo scored 22 points and recovered 8 rebounds. He continued serving this role more frequently for the reminder of the season, starting against  Miami, Virginia and Wake Forest in the ACC tournament.<ref name="NCAA"/> Virginia Tech was included in the NCAA Tournament. Vassallo started two games before the team was eliminated, recording 11 points, 12 rebounds and 3 assists.<ref name="NCAA"/> 

He served as Virginia Tech's starting small forward throughout the 2007-08 season, starting in 35 games and leading the team in minutes played. Vassallo recorded more assists in this season than his freshman and sophomore years, tying his career-high once.<ref name="NCAA"/> He also set a career-high in blocks (3) against [[Liberty University|Liberty]]. His offensive role within the team was expanded, leading the Hokies in points per game (16.9), scoring over 10 points in 33 out of 35 games, including all against ACC competition.<ref name="NCAA"/> He recorded career highs in field goal attempts, reaching his 1,000th point and concluding the season with 1,174 raking 29th within Virginia Tech's all time leaders. His season-high was 27 against [[Georgia Institute of Technology|Georgia Tech]]. Vassallo was third among the Hokies in rebounds with an average of 4.6, he tied his career-high of 11 twice and recorded two double-doubles.<ref name="NCAA"/> When Virginia Tech won the Aeropostale Holiday Festival defeating [[St. John's University (New York)|St. John's]], he was named the event's Most Valuable Player. Vassallo led the Hokies in scoring during the ACC Tournament and recorded 21 assists. After the season concluded, he received All-ACC, [[National Association of Basketball Coaches]] All-District and ACC Tournament Second-Team recognitions.<ref name="NCAA"/> In his final season with the Hokies, Vassallo earned averages of 19.1 points per game, 2.6 assists per game and 6.2 rebounds per game. This marked an steady increase in blocks per game, steals per game, assists per game, points per game and rebounds per game throughout his college career.<ref name="Senior">{{cite web| url=http://techhoops.com/2009/03/02/senior-moments-ad-vassallo-and-cheick-diakite/| title=Senior Moments | A.D. Vassallo and Cheick Diakite| publisher=TechHoops.com| date=2009-03-02| accessdate=2010-07-18}}</ref> All of these stats increased with time, without experiencing a drop. Vassallo's served as the team's offensive leader. In a game against [[University of Wisconsin System|Wisconsin]] he scored 24 points during the second half, including six 3-point field goals, to finish with 30.<ref name="Senior"/> In January 2009, Vassallo scored 29 points versus Virginia. He was also able to perform well against high-seeded teams, scoring 15 consecutive points against [[Duke University|Duke]] on February 28, 2010.<ref name="Senior"/> By March 2009, Vassallo was already eighth in Virginia Tech's all-time scoring list with 1,698 points. On March 18, 2009, he scored 33 points and recovered 12 rebounds to surpass [[Zabian Dowdell]] in the list, becoming the Hokies's best offensive player since [[Bimbo Coles]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.collegiatetimes.com/stories/13264/dukes-of-hazzard-tech-survives-duquesne-in-two-ots/print| title=Dukes of Hazzard: Tech survives Duquesne in two OTs| author=Alex Jackson| publisher=CollegiateTimes.com| date=2009-03-18| accessdate=2010-07-17}}</ref><ref name="Senior"/> Vassallo finished his NCAA career with 1,822 points, finishing fifth in Virginia Tech's history, he also set a record for scored 3-point shots with 267.<ref name="points"/> He was included in the All-ACC third team and NABC All-District second team.<ref name="points">{{cite web| url=http://www.hokiesports.com/notebook/2009/04/#000650| title=Vassallo to compete in Portsmouth Invitational Tournament| publisher=HokieSports.com| date=2009-04-07| accessdate=2010-07-17}}</ref> Vassallo's final amateur tournament was the [[Portsmouth Invitational Tournament]], where he scored 21, 10 and 11 points in his team's third-place finish.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.hokiesports.com/notebook/2009/04/#000651| title=Vassallo leads team to opening round win in PIT| publisher=HokieSports.com| date=2009-04-09| accessdate=2010-07-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.hokiesports.com/notebook/2009/04/#000653| title=Vassallo's team falls in PIT semis| publisher=HokieSports.com| date=2009-04-11| accessdate=2010-07-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.hokiesports.com/notebook/2009/04/#000654| title=Vassallo's team finishes third in PIT| publisher=HokieSports.com| date=2009-04-12| accessdate=2010-07-17}}</ref>

==Baloncesto Superior Nacional==
Vassallo debuted in the [[Baloncesto Superior Nacional]] tournament on April 17, 2009, scoring 22 points against the [[Gigantes de Carolina (basketball)|Gigantes de Carolina]]. He closed his first week scoring 26 and 19 points in games versus the [[Vaqueros de Bayam<U+00F3>n]] and [[Cangrejeros de Santurce (basketball)|Cangrejeros de Santurce]], as well as capturing 15 rebounds in these two games. He closed April scoring 17 and 19 points against the [[Atl<U+00E9>ticos de San Germ<U+00E1>n]] and [[Piratas de Quebradillas]]. On May 2, 2009, Vassallo scored 26 and captured 7 rebounds in a game versus the [[Leones de Ponce (basketball)|Leones de Ponce]], before taking a hiatus of three weeks while he participated in NBA training camps. Upon returning, he scored 34 and recovered 7 rebounds in his first game. On May 30, 2009, Vassallo scored 53 points versus the [[Indios de Mayag<U+00FC>ez (basketball)|Indios de Mayag<U+00FC>ez]], recording the highest amount of points in his life and tying the career-high of his father's BSN career.<ref>{{cite book| title=Deslumbrante Angel Vassallo| author=Jos<U+00E9> R. Ort<U+00FA>zar| publisher=''[[El Vocero]]''| language=Spanish| date=2009-06-01| chapter=Deportes}}</ref> He closed this week scoring 36 points and 9 rebounds against Ponce. From June 10 - 16, Vassallo scored 30, 14,18 and 26 points in games against the [[Mets de Guaynabo (basketball)|Mets de Guaynabo]], Mayag<U+00FC>ez, Bayam<U+00F3>n and Carolina, capturing 32 rebounds. In his last two games of the season, Vassallo scored 48 points and recovered 12 rebounds in games versus the [[Grises de Humacao]] and [[Capitanes de Arecibo]]. In his first BSN All-Star Game, he scored 11 points and recovered 3 rebounds. Since he only played 15 games for the Criollos, Vassallo was not included in the league<U+2019>s leader boards. However, during these games he recorded an higher average than all of the players included in the boards, with 25.6 points per game, in contrast to the league's scoring champion, Jesse Pellot Rosa, who had 23.48 points per game. Despite the elimination of the Criollos, Vassallo received 25 out of 28 votes in the "Rookie of the Year" elections.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.primerahora.com/diario/noticia/baloncesto/acciondeportiva/angel_daniel_vassallo_es_el_novato_del_ano_en_el_bsn/317354| title=<U+00C1>ngel Daniel Vassallo es el novato del a<U+00F1>o en el BSN| publisher=''[[Primera Hora (Guaynabo)|Primera Hora]]''| language=Spanish| date=2009-07-20| accessdate=2009-10-17}}</ref> The Criollos recessed prior to the 2010 BSN season and the Gallitos de Isabela earned the rights of his contract. Vassallo joined the team during the playoffs, but the team was swept by the Vaqueros in their series.<ref>{{cite book| title=Con otra espuela Isabela| author=Carlos Rosa Rosa| publisher=''[[El Nuevo D<U+00ED>a]]''| language=Spanish| date=2010-05-26| chapter=Deportes}}</ref> His season average were 25.6 points per game and 6.7 rebounds per game.

==Ligue Nationale de Basketball==
On October 3, 2009, Vassallo debuted in the [[Ligue Nationale de Basketball]] for [[Paris-Levallois Basket]] scoring 14 points and 7 rebounds.<ref name="LNB">{{cite web| url=http://www.lnb.fr/index.php?pid=9&id=A45904&from=2009&type=1| title=Vassallo Angel Daniel: Match par match| publisher=[[Ligue Nationale de Basketball]]| language=French| accessdate=2010-07-17}}</ref> On the second date against Union Poitiers Basket 86, he improved to 21 points and 10 rebounds. In his third game, Vassallo scored 14 of his 22 points in the last quarter and recovered 6 rebounds.<ref name="LNB"/> This pattern continued on Paris' first game against [[JDA Dijon]], where he had 19 points and 6 rebounds. On October 31, 2009, Vassallo recorded his second double-double, but the team lost.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.parislevallois.com/index.php/plcontent/freearticle/html/(itemid)/6703/(layout)/sport| title=Paris Levallois subit la loi de Chalon| publisher=[[Paris-Levallois Basket]]| accessdate=2010-07-18}}</ref> A week later he recorded his worst game of the season in a 61-75 loss to [[Le Mans Sarthe Basket]]. Paris managed to win its next game against [[ASVEL Lyon-Villeurbanne]], with Vassallo scoring 24 points. On November 24, 2009, he had perfect field goal and free throw percentages, but the team lost by 14 points to [[JA Vichy]].<ref name="LNB"/> Four days later Vassallo scored 29 and recovered 6 rebounds against [[SPO Rouen Basket]]. In his first game of December, he scored 7 out of eleven field goal attempts in a victory over [[Hy<U+00E8>res-Toulon Var Basket]]. In his last two games of the year, Vassallo recorded 18 and 21 points.<ref name="LNB"/>

In the LNB All-Star Game, Vassallo played for the Foreign-Star team, leading all scorers with 22 points and 7 rebounds.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.lnb.fr/index.php?pid=50&id_article=17958| title=All Star Game 2009 - Les fran<U+00E7>ais remportent le match des <U+00E9>toiles| publisher=Ligue Nationale de Basketball| language=French| date=2009-12-30| accessdate=2009-12-30}}</ref> Paris opened the second half of the season with a win over [[Chorale Roanne Basket]] and two losses against [[Strasbourg IG]] and [[Entente Orl<U+00E9>anaise]]. Vassallo continued scoring in double figures during this period, recording 14, 10 and 18 points.<ref name="LNB"/> From this point onwards, Paris would play in rematches against the team faced during the early part of the first half. During the following weeks, the team defeated Poitiers and Dijon, but lost against [[SLUC Nancy]] and [[<U+00C9>S Chalon-sur-Sa<U+00F4>ne]].<ref name="LNB"/> Vassallo contributed 14, 13, 11 and 19 points and recovered 18 collective rebounds. On February 26, 2010, Le Mans was able to limit him to 5 field goal attempts and 1 rebound, but he was able to record a season-high 6 assists.<ref name="LNB"/> In victories over ASVEL, Rouen and Hy<U+00E8>res-Toulon, Vassallo scored 21, 29 and 15 points and recovered 14 rebounds. In April he entered a brief offensive slump, only being successful in 13 out of 34 field-goal attempts in games against [[Cholet Basket]] and [[STB Le Havre]].<ref name="LNB"/> Vassallo recovered by scoring 21, 29 and 12 points. Paris advanced to the playoffs, being placed in a bracket against Le Mans. The team lost both games, but Vassallo scored 40 points and recovered 7 rebounds.<ref name="LNB"/> During the off-season, Vassallo announced that he had been invited to the 2010 NBA Summer League and would also participate in a [[Toronto Raptors]] try-out, preventing his participation in the [[2010 Centrobasket]].<ref>{{cite book| title=Angel Vassallo no va| author=Ra<U+00FA>l <U+00C1>lzaga | publisher=''[[Primera Hora (Guaynabo)|Primera Hora]]''| language=Spanish| date=2010-06-25| chapter=Deportes}}</ref> However, prior to the event's inauguration, he signed a contract with ASVEL.

==International career==
During his youth, Vassallo  was part of Puerto Rico's Junior National Team. His first major competition with this team was the 2003 FIBA World Championship for Junior Men. Throughout the event he accumulated averages of 8 points and 6 rebounds per game.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.puertorico2009.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/player/p/pid/44406/pid2//sid/3163/tid/349/tid2//_/2003_World_Championship_for_Junior_Men/index.html| title=2003 World Championship for Junior Men: 12 - Angel Daniel Vassallo| publisher=[[International Basketball Federation|FIBA]]| accessdate-2010-07-17}}</ref> At the 2005 FIBA U21 World Championship for Men, Vassallo gathered statistics of 8.6 points and 4 rebounds per game.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.puertorico2009.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/player/p/pid/44406/pid2//sid/3234/tid/349/tid2//_/2005_FIBA_U21_World_Championship_for_Men/index.html| title=2005 FIBA U21 World Championship For Men: 12 - Angel Daniel Vassallo| publisher=[[International Basketball Federation|FIBA]]| accessdate=2010-07-17}}</ref> His first participation with the senior Puerto Rico national basketball team was at the 2008 Centrobasket Championship for Men, where he served as the shooting guard backup behind [[Carmelo Lee]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.puertorico2009.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/player/p/pid/44406/pid2//sid/6401/tid/349/tid2//_/2008_Centrobasket_Championship_for_Men/index.html| title=2008 Centrobasket Championship for Men: 11 - Angel Daniel Vassallo| publisher=[[International Basketball Federation|FIBA]]| accessdate=2010-07-17}}</ref> He recorded 6 points and 1.2 per game in limited time, while the team won the gold medal. He returned to this role at the 2009 Marchand Continental Cup, an exhibition tournament, where he improved to 10 points and 3 rebounds. Next was the 2009 FIBA Americas Championship for Men, a qualificatory tournament for the [[2010 FIBA World Championship]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.puertorico2009.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/player/p/pid/44406/pid2//sid/6603/tid/349/tid2//_/2009_Marchand_Continental_Cup/index.html| title=2009 Marchand Continental Cup: 8 - Angel Daniel Vassallo| publisher=[[International Basketball Federation|FIBA]]| accessdate=2010-07-17}}</ref> There Vassallo had statistics of 7.3 points and 3.4 rebounds, including a perfect game against Brasil, where he scored 8 of 8 field goal attempts and a free throw attempt.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fibaamericas.com/noticiasread4.asp?r=TOENQPAMMH&t=BIVRPKNDXU| title=PUR/BRA - Juego perfecto de Vassallo le da victoria a Puerto Rico| author=Luis Modestti| publisher=[[FIBA Americas]]| language=Spanish| date=2009-09-04| accessdate=2010-07-17}}</ref> Puerto Rico won the silver medal and qualified.

